By introducing autonomous characters with conflicting goals—predators utilizing a "seek" behavior and prey utilizing a "flee" behavior —the simulation produces highly complex, emergent survival dynamics. 

Group Formation: When the predators are distant, the prey agents behave according to standard flocking rules. 
                 Cohesion and alignment take priority, causing the prey to cluster tightly together and move in unified groups across the screen.  

Escape Behavior: As a predator enters the "flee perception radius" of the prey, the localized flee force exponentially overrides the flocking forces. 
                 The prey agents exhibit a rapid "burst" or scattering effect, breaking their unified formation to maximize distance from the predator. 
                 Because the prey agents have slightly higher maneuverability (max force) than the predators, they can perform sharp evasive turns.  

Splitting and Merging: The most striking emergent behavior occurs when a predator dives directly into the center of a dense flock. 
                       The flock instantly splits in half to flow around the predator, creating a localized vacuum. 
                       Once the predator passes through, the remaining prey agents fall back under the influence of the cohesion rule. 
                       They seek out the nearest neighbors and seamlessly merge back into a single unified group behind the predator, demonstrating fluid, adaptive crowd behavior without any centralized control.  
